on a practical level, research shows that we tend to gravitate toward the animal with which we were raised.those who love felines, though, were found to be less traditional, more creative and more neurotic.parents with young children generally have energetic dogs the kids can play with outside, while single people or older people are more inclined to have the more low-key cat.apartment dwellers in urban areas are more likely to have cats or small dogs, while families living in the suburbs are more apt to have larger dogs like retrievers or bull mastiffs.those who define themselves as "dog people" are more extroverted, more agreeable and more conscientious than self-described "cat people."scientists at major academic institutions have devoted time and resources to understanding why people become one or the other."dogs there are very rarely pets because they're considered vermin." going deeper than geography or our upbringing, though, scientists believe the selection of species can say a lot about people.dogs win in the popularity race, with 39 percent of u.s. households owning at least one dog, compared with 33 percent of u.s. households owning at least one cat.like the choice between coke or pepsi, or chocolate or vanilla, how you respond to cats versus dogs could say a lot about you."cats are more independent and so are their owners," martha auspitz said.cat people, they say, are simply smarter.over at the black diamond cat show in kimberton, pa., cat owners were telling a different story, saying intelligence is the key difference between dog and cat owners.another big factor is living space and age."cat people are a little more aloof, because that's just how cats are."dog people are a little more outgoing," a dog owner at the westminster dog show told abc news.